<Author>Road_and_Travel_Wise
<Content>Our Favourite Pick From All The Places We Stayed in Europe! Just back with my partner from our 10 week trip across Europe (visiting 10 countries and 28 cities) and time to write some reviews! Having stayed at so many BB's, Hostels and smaller, family run hotels during the course of our trip - we have a fair base on which to make some comparitive critiques - and our overall favorite is: L'Antic Espai in Barcelona where we spent a very pleasant 5 nights!! Having to keep to a fairly tight budget, we chose their smallest room, which by European standards was economical for the two of us and, as is typical, was small but still very comfortably appointed with the most important detail: a very comfortable bed/matress and spanking clean, modern bathroom ensuite (with shower). Extras included a tastefully decorated room, air conditioning, free WiFi internet (so we could book our next flight segments), Laundry facilities (arrange with staff), an LCD TV and personal DVD player. Incredibly we saw another Trip Adviser member complain of lack of English language TV stations in the room??! This is Spain - the only country on our trip where we found English language programming available in our room was in England... Incidentally, the hostal have an impressive collection (for varied tastes) of DVD's available which we enjoyed a couple of nights before drifting off to sleep. The location couldn't have been better - with easy access to the metro, and walking distance to many good bars and restaurants and the famous La Rambla. We had no trouble finding the place from the hostal's instructions and on arrival, were treated to no less than some of the local sparkling Cava (bottled under their own 'house' label??!!) from the owners, Abel and Sergio - in genuine antique cristal champagne glasses - nice start to our vacation in this marvellous city. In fact we found both themselves and the rest of the reception staff to be very helpful and knowledgable on everything from where to dine, some good clubs to check out, how to use the local transportation and of course some of the best tourist sites to visit. We opted for breakfast in our room all except one morning (have to request the night before (no problem!), and was typically European: delicious, strong black coffee with cream, orange juice, toast (real butter!), croissonts and yummy Greek style yoghurt... The big difference was in the way it was served... on genuine antique china with real silver cutlery - a touch we've found only in a few high end botique hotels these days... We really enjoyed the ambience created in the tasteful decor from the entrance hall, to the common sitting room, to our room itself with a wonderful collection of antiques which Sergio and Abel have hand chosen during their travels prior to reforming and opening the Hostal. Alas, chatting with them over drinks, one can easily perceive that the creation of L'Antic Espai was a labour of love for them, indeed fulfilling their dream, and not simply creating yet another boring, run of the mill accommodation option for visitors to Barcelona. (Even the old hidraulic tiles, restored and set into the floor of our room have a story, and Abel and Sergio will be happy to tell it over a drink if you have the time as we did...). May those who deserve as special a place as this is come to visit, we will be back and highly recommend it!Richard and Rob 
